<article>
    <h1>Ju&#xAD;liana Chan (right), 36, founder, ar&#xAD;chi&#xAD;tect and artist, NS Chan Stu&#xAD;dio</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201031/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-31"><time>2020-10-31</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>My hus­band and I re­cently bought a gam­ing chair from Se­cret­lab and it has now be­come my favourite chair.</p>
    <p>Work­ing from home dur­ing the coro­n­avirus pan­demic has been es­pe­cially chal­leng­ing. As an ar­chi­tect and artist, I find my­self eas­ily chalk­ing up 12 hours or more at my desk.</p>
    <p>I can re­mem­ber how in the past, be­fore I started my de­sign stu­dio, I sat on sim­ple of­fice fab­ric chairs in my pre­vi­ous work­places. To man­age body aches from poor pos­ture, my col­leagues and I would im­pro­vise by us­ing old pa­per boxes and stacks of out­dated ten­der draw­ings to rest our feet for thigh sup­port and use cush­ions for lum­bar sup­port.</p>
    <p>I suf­fered back­aches for many years but af­ter mak­ing changes to my chair, my con­di­tion has im­proved con­sid­er­ably.</p>
    <p>The Se­cret­lab chair, which cost about $600, is com­fort­able and sturdy. I like to take fre­quent breaks from my com­puter screen, and to just lean back to rest my shoul­ders and neck.</p>
    <p>Its high back and neck­rest, with its safety lock­ing mech­a­nism, have helped to re­duce aches and strains when I opt for a re­clin­ing po­si­tion. Also, I like its fine-weave fab­ric tex­ture, which feels soft.</p>
    <p>Th­ese small de­tails make a big dif­fer­ence to me when spend­ing hours in front of the com­puter.</p>

